---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";

const updated = "June 28, 2026";
---

<Base
  title="copyright & dmca policy - embody.tools"
  description="How to report copyright infringement in the Collection, how to file a counter-notice, and our repeat-infringer policy. Plain language, real process."
>
  <section class="page-section legal-hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">copyright</p>
    <h1>copyright &amp; dmca policy</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      The Collection is built on people sharing work they have the right to share. When
      that goes wrong, this is how we put it right &mdash; how to report infringing
      material, how to push back if your work was removed by mistake, and what happens to
      repeat offenders.
    </p>
    <p class="legal-updated mono">Last updated: {updated}</p>
  </section>

  <article class="page-section tight legal-body">
    <h2>Reporting infringement</h2>
    <p>
      If you believe a specimen in the Collection copies your work without permission, you
      have two paths. For a quick flag, use the <strong>report</strong> control on the
      specimen and pick &ldquo;copyright&rdquo; &mdash; that lands in our moderation queue.
      For a formal takedown under the U.S. Digital Millennium Copyright Act (DMCA), send a
      written notice to our copyright agent with the details below. We respond to valid
      notices promptly, typically by removing or disabling the material.
    </p>

    <h2>Filing a DMCA notice</h2>
    <p>
      To be valid, your notice needs to include all of the following. Missing pieces will
      slow us down or make the notice ineffective:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>Your physical or electronic signature.</li>
      <li>
        Identification of the copyrighted work you say has been infringed (or a
        representative list, if there are several).
      </li>
      <li>
        Identification of the infringing material and <strong>enough detail to find it</strong>
        &mdash; the specimen URL is ideal.
      </li>
      <li>
        Your contact information: name, address, telephone number, and email.
      </li>
      <li>
        A statement that you have a <strong>good-faith belief</strong> the use isn&rsquo;t
        authorized by the copyright owner, its agent, or the law.
      </li>
      <li>
        A statement that the information in your notice is accurate, and &mdash; under
        <strong>penalty of perjury</strong> &mdash; that you are the copyright owner or
        authorized to act on the owner&rsquo;s behalf.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Where to send it</h2>
    <p>
      Send your notice to our designated copyright agent:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Designated Copyright Agent</strong>, The Experiential Company, LLC</li>
      <li>Email: <a href="mailto:rosco@tec.design">rosco@tec.design</a></li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      A mailing address for formal service is available on request. Email reaches us
      fastest, so please use it where you can.
    </p>

    <h2>After we receive a valid notice</h2>
    <p>
      We remove or disable access to the material in question and let the person who
      published it know why, passing along your notice so they can respond. If they file a
      valid counter-notice (below), we&rsquo;ll forward it to you; unless you tell us
      you&rsquo;ve filed a court action to keep the material down, we may restore it after
      10 to 14 business days, as the DMCA contemplates.
    </p>

    <h2>Filing a counter-notice</h2>
    <p>
      If your specimen was removed and you believe that was a mistake or a misidentification
      &mdash; for example, you hold the rights, or the use is permitted &mdash; you can send
      a counter-notice to the same agent. It needs to include:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>Your physical or electronic signature.</li>
      <li>
        Identification of the material that was removed and the location where it appeared
        before removal.
      </li>
      <li>
        A statement, under <strong>penalty of perjury</strong>, that you have a good-faith
        belief the material was removed as a result of mistake or misidentification.
      </li>
      <li>
        Your name, address, and telephone number, plus a statement that you consent to the
        jurisdiction of the federal court for your district (or, if you&rsquo;re outside the
        U.S., the district where we may be found), and that you will accept service of
        process from the person who filed the original notice.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Repeat infringers</h2>
    <p>
      Accounts that repeatedly infringe others&rsquo; rights are suspended or terminated.
      We keep a record of notices we act on so we can recognize a pattern.
    </p>

    <h2>One important caution</h2>
    <p>
      Don&rsquo;t file a notice or a counter-notice you don&rsquo;t mean. Under U.S. law
      (DMCA section 512(f)), anyone who <strong>knowingly misrepresents</strong> that
      material is infringing &mdash; or was wrongly removed &mdash; can be held liable for
      damages, including costs and legal fees. If you&rsquo;re not sure whether something is
      infringing, talk to a lawyer before you send anything.
    </p>

    <h2>Outside the United States</h2>
    <p>
      The DMCA is a U.S. law, but copyright isn&rsquo;t only a U.S. concern. If you&rsquo;re
      a rights-holder elsewhere, send us the same information and we&rsquo;ll act on
      legitimate claims under the applicable law just the same.
    </p>

    <p class="legal-sign mono">
      See also the <a href="/terms">Terms of Service</a> and the
      <a href="/privacy">Privacy Policy</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
